Author: cipi#4502
Content:
```sudo apt-get install gcc-5 g++-5 gcc-6 g++-6 gcc-7 g++-7
sudo update-alternatives --remove-all gcc
sudo update-alternatives --remove-all g++
sudo update-alternatives --install /usr/bin/gcc gcc /usr/bin/gcc-6 60 --slave /usr/bin/g++ g++ /usr/bin/g++-6
sudo update-alternatives --install /usr/bin/gcc gcc /usr/bin/gcc-5 40 --slave /usr/bin/g++ g++ /usr/bin/g++-5
sudo update-alternatives --install /usr/bin/gcc gcc /usr/bin/gcc-7 50 --slave /usr/bin/g++ g++ /usr/bin/g++-7

# switch gcc with
sudo update-alternatives --config gcc```

Author: cipi#4502
Content: then you have all compilers and can switch between them with the last command -> problem solved

Author: cipi#4502
Content: the above will work though, if you have the compilers installed, regardless of their source... but best is to fix this... gcc > 5 is much stricter when dealing with warnings, many things where gcc-5 was showing a warning are now treated as errors... if you know how, you can alter the behavior, but that would need you to pass some additional compiler settings
